snippet.textDisplay:
Besides making a device more water and dirt resistant, wireless charging is attractive to me because it doesn't have a physical connection that can be damaged when you try to remove a device without first removing the connection. I mean, the connector on something like the MS Surface achieves a similar result by using magnets to replace a physical (friction) hold, so that the risk of causing damage to the connector is less, and there are magnetic USB adapters for a similar effect, so wireless charging isn't the only way to do it. But that's why I like wireless charging.

Why I don't like wireless charging is that it makes recharging a device dependent on a bulky appliance. You better have some serious battery life, or a wired charging option.

So this fancy charging stations doesn't solve that drawback. At all.

snippet.textDisplay: Why do they even call it wireless charging? it's not really wireless at all. The device you are charging, still has to make a direct connection/contact with the charger (that has a wire). Essentially, it's wired, but with a different connector on the end of the wire - one you have to physically plug into the device, one that you do not. It's not like wifi or radio or bluetooth that actually transmits through the air.

snippet.textDisplay:
I want a charging pad with a grid of tiny red/green LEDs in the surface, so that when it detects a phone's coil that isn't aligned well enough to charge, it outlines the phone in red LEDs, when it's partially aligned for low-speed charging the LEDs shift to orange/yellow, and when it's fully align they're green. Also a small ambient light sensor so the LEDs dim in a dark room to barely-noticeable brightness.

Basically, it appears place-anywhere to charge is a hard mechanical problem to solve. And when you have hard constraints, good UX can often save the day.
